  <article aria-labelledby="hard-centre-title">
    <h1 id="hard-centre-title">The Hard Centre Manifesto</h1>

    <p class="site-intro">I stand in the Hard Centre.</p>
    <p>The centre isn’t soft—it’s the hardest road of all. It means doing what works, even when it upsets both left and right. Not splitting the difference. Not being “nice.” Evidence, fairness, and responsibility—for real outcomes in the real world.</p>

    <section aria-labelledby="binary-trap">
      <h2 id="binary-trap">Breaking the Binary Trap</h2>
      <p>Brexit or Remain. Left or Right. Us or Them. These false choices keep us stuck with bad answers. The Hard Centre refuses that game. Like post-war West Germany, surrounded by the wreckage of extremes, we must carve a third way—not compromise, but the only path that delivers.</p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="price-of-progress">
      <h2 id="price-of-progress">The Price of Progress</h2>
      <p>If you want Hard Centre support, the price is non-negotiable: Proportional Representation. Not as a favour. Not as a nice-to-have. As the foundation of adult politics. When every vote counts, parties must build coalitions. Ideology gives way to evidence. Tribalism to pragmatism. Binary thinking to nuance.</p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="hard-centre-values">
      <h2 id="hard-centre-values">What the Hard Centre Stands For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Evidence over ideology:</strong> show me the data, not the doctrine.</li>
        <li><strong>Institutions that work:</strong> defend what functions, reform what fails.</li>
        <li><strong>Democratic legitimacy:</strong> every vote counts equally, every voice matters.</li>
        <li><strong>Principled pragmatism:</strong> strong values, flexible methods.</li>
        <li><strong>Long-term thinking:</strong> governing for the next generation, not the next headline.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="hard-choice">
      <h2 id="hard-choice">The Hard Choice</h2>
      <p>This isn’t about being liked by everyone. It’s about being respected for principles worth the political cost. The Hard Left and Hard Right have their banners. It’s time the Hard Centre had one too.</p>
      <p class="site-intro">The centre holds—not because it’s weak, but because it’s strong enough to bear the weight of reality.</p>
    </section>
  </article>

